SIMPLE: fourth
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fourth
<hw>Fourth</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>fourthe</ets>, <ets>ferthe</ets>, <ets>feorthe</ets>, AS.
<ets>fe⟦oacute⟧r⟦edh⟧a</ets>, fr. <ets>fe⟦oacute⟧wer</ets> four.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Next in order after the third; the ordinal of
four.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Forming one of four equal parts into which anything
may be divided.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fourth</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fourth
<hw>Fourth</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of four equal parts
into which one whole may be divided; the quotient of a unit divided by
four.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The interval of two tones and a
semitone, embracing four diatonic degrees of the scale; the subdominant
of any key.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One coming next in order after the third.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The Fourth</b></col>, <cd>specifically, in the United
States, the fourth day of July, the anniversary of the declaration of
American independence; <as>as, to celebrate <ex>the
Fourth</ex></as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fourthly</ent>⟦br⟧
